post_cb({"8924604": {"ParentId": "8924088", "CommentCount": "3", "Body": "<p>c++11 standard tells this:</p>\n<p>23.3.2.8 / 3</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8924088_8924604_0\">The e\ufb00ect of calling front() or back() for a zero-sized array is unde\ufb01ned.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since the behaviour is undefined, anything can happen. You were lucky to get a crash.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "476681", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "8924604", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2012-01-19T10:37:41.557", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-19T10:37:41.557"}, "8924123": {"ParentId": "8924088", "CommentCount": "5", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8924088_8924123_0\">do we need to check the length of the vector before calling back() ?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In a word: yes. This is your bug, your vector is empty so there is no \"back\" element.</p>\n<p>The documentation should say (if it says anything at all) that calling <code>back()</code> on an empty vector causes <em>undefined behavior</em>, not that it returns an undefined value.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "19563", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "8924123", "Score": "13", "CreationDate": "2012-01-19T10:03:09.617", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-19T10:03:09.617"}, "8924088": {"CommentCount": "3", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8924123", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "198011", "CreationDate": "2012-01-19T10:01:15.280", "LastActivityDate": "2012-01-19T13:30:55.467", "LastEditDate": "2012-01-19T13:30:55.467", "ViewCount": "4094", "FavoriteCount": "0", "Title": "Why does the call to std::vector::back() crash my program", "Id": "8924088", "Score": "6", "Body": "<p>I am not sure what's wrong with this code :</p>\n<pre><code>std::vector&lt;int&gt; myVector(0);\n\nif (myVector.back() == 12)\n    myVector.push_back(12);\n</code></pre>\n<p>It seems that calling back() on an empty vector crashes the program.  </p>\n<p>I don't understand why it's crashing? Do we need to check the length of the vector before calling <code>back()</code>? or is possible that it's 